#Text=Hovenden Walker

#Text=Rear-Admiral Sir Hovenden Walker ( 1656 or 1666 – 1725 or 1728 ) was a British naval officer noted for , during Queen Anne 's War , having led an abortive 1711 expedition against Quebec City , then the capital of New France .
#Text=Early career
#Text=Walker entered Trinity College Dublin in 1678 but did not take a degree and subsequently joined the Royal Navy .
#Text=He probably visited North America in 1686 , reaching Boston aboard the frigate HMS Dartmouth . [ 1 ]
#Text=Walker was promoted to captain about 1692 and saw action near the Lizard while in command of the fourth-rate HMS Foresight in around 1696 .

#Text=In 1701 he joined the fleet under Sir George Rooke at Cadiz , and shortly afterwards , as commodore , took command of a detachment charged with cooperating in an attack on Guadeloupe and Martinique , which was unsuccessful .
#Text=This failure did not damage his career , though ; in 1706 he assisted in the relief of Barcelona , and two years later was appointed to command the squadron before Dunkirk .
#Text=In March 1711 he was promoted to rear-admiral and was also given a knighthood . [ 1 ]
#Text=Expedition to Canada
#Text=On April 3 , 1711 , the new rear-admiral of the white squadron was made commander-in-chief of a secret naval expedition aimed at the conquest of New France .
#Text=His expedition was to attack Quebec in combination with a land expedition led by Colonel Francis Nicholson . [ 2 ]

#Text=On July 30 , the expedition consisting of nine ships of war , two bomb vessels and 60 transports and tenders , British and colonial , with some 7,500 troops and marines aboard set sail from Boston .

#Text=On the morning of the 18th of August , just as the expedition was about to enter the Saint Lawrence River , the wind began to blow hard from the northwest , and Walker was forced to seek shelter in Gaspé Bay .

#Text=On the morning of the 20th , the wind veered to the southeast , and he was able to advance slowly past the western extremity of Anticosti Island before it died down and thick fog blanketed both shore and fleet .
#Text=By the 22nd , the wind had freshened from the southeast , and there were intermittent breaks in the fog , but not sufficient to give sight of land .
#Text=After consulting his pilots , Walker gave the signal to head the fleet southward . [ 1 ]
#Text=Walker had thought he was in mid-stream when he issued the order .
#Text=In fact , he was about seven leagues north of his proper course , and in the grasp of strong currents which steered his ships towards the northwest .
#Text=Aided by an easterly wind , the fleet was gradually closing on the " North Shore , " which in the vicinity of Île-aux-Oeufs ( Egg Island ) runs almost north and south .

#Text=When a captain reported that land had been sighted , presumably dead ahead , Walker assumed that he was approaching the south shore , and ordered the fleet to wear , and bring-to on the other tack .
#Text=Not many minutes later he was again summoned from his bed , and hurrying upon deck in dressing gown and slippers saw breakers " all round us . "
#Text=By that time the whole fleet was heading for the " North Shore , " or more accurately , the coast to the westward ; ships in the van were already plunging on the edge of the breakers . [ 1 ]
#Text=Once recovered from the shock , Walker made all available sail , and stood from the shore towards mid-channel .
#Text=Up to this time a gale had been blowing almost directly on shore , and had it continued it is doubtful if many of the fleet could have survived .

#Text=However , in the early morning of the next day , the wind dropped , and this lull was followed by a shift of wind which enabled most of the ships to slip their anchors and escape the shoals on either quarter .
#Text=Altogether , seven transports and one storeship were lost .
#Text=Out of a total of 1,390 , 740 soldiers ( including 35 women attached to the regiments ) and probably 150 sailors were either drowned or died from exposure on shore .
#Text=Walker cruised in the neighbourhood of Île-aux-Oeufs for two days in an effort to save what men and stores he could .
#Text=Then , following a council of war , he decided to abandon the assault on Quebec . [ 1 ]
#Text=Later life
#Text=Walker returned to London in October 1711 , where he was not censured for his conduct in the expedition .
#Text=In 1712 he was appointed commodore of the Jamaica Station . [ 3 ]
#Text=He returned a year later to England . [ 1 ]

#Text=Walker 's journal , recounting the events of 1711 , was published in 1720 and was edited by Gerald S. Graham and re-published jointly by the Champlain Society and the Navy Records Society in 1953 . [ 2 ]
